# Improved Research Summary

Artificial intelligence is increasingly used in healthcare to support disease diagnosis, medical imaging, drug discovery, patient monitoring, and administrative tasks. Potential benefits include faster diagnoses, improved operational efficiency, personalized treatment recommendations, and better use of healthcare resources.

However, AI adoption also presents significant challenges. These include concerns about patient privacy, cybersecurity, algorithmic bias, transparency, regulatory compliance, and accountability for clinical decisions. AI systems may also perform differently across patient populations depending on the quality and diversity of training data.

Current research suggests that AI is most effective when used to support healthcare professionals rather than replace human clinical judgment. A balanced evaluation should consider both its opportunities and limitations while relying on evidence from peer-reviewed research.

